< name>
Suave Sloth< /name>
< review>
I was quite displeased with this place. To Start off anyone going here please note that this place is clearly set up as a delivery or a 'fast food' ramen place. The reason I say this is their staff lack any sense of customer service. We were not greeted, we were not helped to a seat or even menus given to us and while we were sitting the staff did not come to take the order, we had to go up and order and even pour the water ourselves.

The food itself was the most disappointing part. The broth which was luke warm at best was swimming in bean sprouts, so much so that you had to actually look for the noodles. The noodles themselves tasted around the quality of top ramen that had been just soaking longer in broth. The egg that came with the ramen also had been soaking far too long in the broth as it fell apart upon picking it up, these eggs are normally kept cold so I am unsure as to why they were not kept cold here.

They have been open for about a month now so I would figure they would at least have the proper kitchen equipment to make ramen, I did not see any of that equipment however leading me to think that this place was set up without prior knowledge or research into running a resturant or running a ramen shop.

Everyone, do yourself a favor and take the extra time to drive up to Irvine and get some real ramen, this place is more expensive than the well established ramen places up north.</review>

Kids liked bouncers overall but wanted more that we haven't been allowed due to money making by that place that is on priority in this place. And we actually are ready to pay more to have sth more convenient for us not to be in rush so that many important things have been forgotten at all.
BUT ORGANIZATIONS is really really bad with a conveyer without possibility to go to the party room almost at all. We're the host who has our kid's birthday vision not yours. We need time to prepare everything how we dreamed not how you do for everyone the same! Saturday was really busy with the party right in front of us and right behind us...really packed, no possibility to breath, stop to think and don't forget sth important that was on mind.
So our birthday kid didn't get presents direct from his guests,  we saw them in a huge plastic bag at home only!
They're making so much money but first bouncer in a first room had a hole we felt wind out of it, party room throne is really old - guys really for such big money you make? Please update them! Or poor people who still visit you.

< review>
I ordered internet Wi-Fi from AT&T and booked an installation date for Saturday, September 21st from 09 AM to 11 AM. When the installation person arrived in my flat, he communicated a mistake, reported to be happening 'quite often' with AT&T, regarding the nature of my account being set as 'business', even though I applied for internet service to my residence. Therefore he strongly suggested that I regularized my status from 'business' to 'residential' before going further with the installation process. As suggested, I used my Saturday afternoon to go back to the same AT&T store in old town Pasadena, CA, to verify what happened. Upon arrival, I was informed that in order to avoid me paying the installation fee they set my account to business and that it was a normal procedure. However, if it is a normal procedure, why did not the installation person know about it? Why do I have to wait another 5 days until the installation happens? They only have an available time on next Wednesday. AT&T plays with its costumers in order to catch them for whatever price, but they forget to communicate these same tricks to their field personnel. I am utterly shocked by the lack of professionalism and respect towards their clients. It is absurd.<//review>

I lost my phone so I tried to activate a sim card for my replacement here earlier. I didn't have my id with me so I was told by an associate to do it on the phone.  I explained I tried calling at the Apple store down the street 5 minutes prior but since AT&T's customer service line only operates from 5am-7pm pst. and it was after 7pm I was advised by Apple to try here... He figured it was worth a shot to call again from the store since he knew he could get on the line with someone... Not a good idea. I waited patiently for 10 minutes before he hands me the phone and says "if you need me I'll be up front." I was on the phone 26:16!! I was transferred to two operators from AT&T answering the same questions to each before the second operator explains he can't help me since I'm calling from an AT&T store & an associate at the store should be able to do it quickly... The whole time I was on hold in the store no one asked how I was doing or if I needed anything, a water would have been amazing... I wasted 35 minutes of my day watching a store full of workers do nothing while a beats pill demo station played generic EDM hits. The painfully awkward small talk & hearing AT&T hold advertisements over and over didn't lighten the vibe at all either. When I finally hung up the phone no one from the staff acknowledged me even though it was on their phone awkwardly out of place for 15%-30% of their shift. <user>116923417257225089322</user><Date>1599241539028< /Date>< Review>
This location of Sweet Veggie has converted their seating to a small market and has switched to takeout. The bento boxes are a great deal! $7.99 for rice or noodles with 4 items. The food rotates everyday and is always interesting. People seem to love the market too. It can be a bit cramped when busy because it is small, but don't let that put you off. Make clear you want take out, order and enjoy!
(There are two tables outside, two chairs each)<//Review>

<review>This is an awesome place that sells Taiwanese Vegetarian food! I used to come her before the COVID 19 pandemic and I can say it looks a lot different. You used to be able to come in, get your own different food they have as well as shaved ice and get drinks like winter melon tea, but now it is made for Togo only. You can‚Äôt still order food, but it would be more of a set meal, like a bento box, and they have transformed the whole ‚Äúdining‚Äù area into a small Taiwanese market!
You can go in here now, pick up some rice, snacks, or some vegetables, while also getting a meal before you check out, and its great! Not only do they sell different things, but they also try to stay close to the type of restaurant they have, so they would have things like vegan jerky, etc. My last trip, I was able to buy different groceries and then was able to get 2 meals for under $9 each, that included a bento box, winter melon tea, pudding (like the ones they have in Taiwan!!) And another side of imitation orange beef.
Now that everyone is slowly starting to get their vaccines, I hope to be able to visit a bit more, but there is always a ease of mind when you visit somewhere that is COVID compliant, and just overall have a safe feeling of ordering food or groceries ! Wished I would have taken some pictures of the food, but ill make sure to do so next time!</review><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOPh0MeH28kVafCqKZ5Mm6WAfyWhN0S4f-KvNEa=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMgAhGXpeUzwi6NtRnFuyP-yMd5vP8hPWOVr0uq=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipN8oekIS9zMdbdfKEiAQ4syAEEcOyAn6CyIMI3X=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pictures><response>None< /response>< gmap_id>

<Rate>5</Rate><text>I used to hate vegitables. And yet every time I go here, even when I try completely new types of veggies, I am always happy with it.

The menu is constantly rotating but there are a few Staples that are usually there, such as their amazing veggie pizza. I've only seen it once, but I really enjoyed their curry. They also have a not-very-spicy mapo tofu that I liked. Some dishes have meat substitutes in them, and while they aren't always particularly good imitations, they are always at least delicious.

This place is a buffet, so you can get as much as you want. You are expected to bus your own table, but in exchange they do not accept tips. That makes this place an even better value proposition. They also include desserts and drinks.

They are very popular right now, so you may want to avoid the most popular times to avoid having a long wait.< /text><Pics>None<//Pics>< resp>

<user_id>117089483423948728582<//user_id>< Name>
Arthur Sun<//Name>
<Time>1552892522100<//Time><Rating>5< /Rating>< review>
A solid Chinese vegetarian buffet - it gets five stars because I'm a little biased as a (mostly) vegetarian myself. Don't come expecting a mind blowing experience, just a satisfying one.

Shifting menu but always expect a broad variety. Consistent things include their beverages and deserts - boba, milk tea, shaved ice and condiments, wintermelon tea, coffee, etc.

Highlights include their amazing medicinal/herbal soup, fried mushrooms, Taiwanese rice noodles (mi fen), sauteed vegetables and whatever tofu dish is around that day. And sometimes their sushi/kimbap is enticing.

If I remember right, it's 8 dollars a person for lunch.

(this review is for their weekday lunches. haven't been to dinner or weekend breakfasts)<//review>

<Text>First timer. Arrived for early dinner at 5:30, the place was clean, quiet and food was fresh. This place is mostly vegan with 1-3 dairy items that consisted of dessert. They have a good variety of all you can eat buffet items. There is no server staff, no tableside service, no tipping allowed, bus your own table, self-serve-to-go, no alcohol kind of place. I don't mind this type of restaurant, but if you like to be catered to or want to get your drink on, then this isn't the place for you. The hostess is charming and took time to explain how their system works, she walked me through the diminutive buffet area, and pointed out the hot & cold food, and dessert/beverage stations. They offer white or brown rice, and their food items are rotated throughout the week, so you may not always see the same items. I enjoyed the taro balls, the pasta with peanut sauce, the fresh steamed veggies, tempura green beans, and sushi items (no fish of course). They offered their take on mafo tofu (mild tasting and not pungent at all), they also had pizza & nachos (with non dairy cheese-no thanks), rice porridge, and other items I didn't get to try out because I got stuffed after my 2nd trip to the buffet (had to leave room for dessert). They offer a build your own shaved ice dessert bar with the fixings, fresh made ice tea and lemonade. Their milktea actually had dairy in it (surprising). Overall, it's what you'd expect from a no-extras kind of place. Which at times is what some of us want---no deep thinking about what to have. The music they played overhead was pleasant and relaxing, and my fambam liked the satisfying eats (options), the desserts (fave: yummy chocolate sponge cake, light as a feather), and that it's a buffet with a price point that can't be beat (winner). Definitely gonna try it again just in case I missed something, and to see if it is consistent in their flavors and options. This just may become a new fave go-to place for a quick bite when there's nothing to prep at home or the chef is on strike (lol). (Psst, there's another one of these in Walnut,  but I much prefer this location, which i didn't know it was the same). Wishing you good eats and great times while #foodsploring.</Text>< Date>

< Text>
I can't say enough nice things about this place so I'll just make a list of everything I like
1. It's cheap for a buffet
2. It's small but the selection you get is always delicious, no wasting time with a giant buffet line trying a little of a billion things, each dish is homemade and cooked with love and you can really taste it
3. No tips! They don't accept them u just basically put ur dirty dishes away for then and enjoy a meal :D
3. If u like meat u will probably like something they have because I kid you not some of the meat immitations they use are so eerily similar a vegan or vegetarian must be thinking they are eating meat.
4. The service is fantastic, the ladies working there are always conscious about your diet and ask and explain if you have any specific questions. But everything is labeled and tells you if it's vegan or vegetarian :D< /Text>

<Time>1541443474634< /Time><Text>Excellent variety of main and side dishes, desserts, and non-alcoholic beverages.  The modest selection of imitation sushi is good, but the best part is most of the items are natural and flavorful - i.e. a few attempts at imitating meat, like fried oysters and sushi meat, while most dishes items are sauteed/cooked vegetables without the heavy gravies or sauces.  It is self service and the carbs, like noodles, are separate from the mains, so you get to take just what you like and sample some things new to you.  (Most vegetarian places either fill you up with a ton of carbs or lots of salad.  Not here.)  This is one place worth the trip and going back to (on the same trip or on different days) - I filled my plate 3 times, and grabbed dessert twice, and I have an athletic physic.  Plus, I'm not even a vegetarian and can say the food is good! < name>
Jon Chia< /name>
<response>None<//response><gmap_id>0x80c32b7525f32cd5:0x83ebcd6d7b309768</gmap_id><text>Full buddhist vegan (no dairy or animal byproducts in food or cooking process. Also no onion, leek, chives, and the rest of the 5 pungent veggies).

Very good place for my parents and friends who are chinese buddhist vegans who are a bit more restricted on their diets.

This is buffet style with usually 8-10 choices of hot food (rotating dishes), consistent selection of cold food, and 3-4 soups. Dessert include shaved ice and some cookies. No soft drinks but milk tea, black tea, and wintermelon tea is offered instead.

They serve Taiwanese style breakfast on Saturday and Sunday morning (Chinese donut, Chinese pancake, eggroll, rice rolls, etc.).

For the price and selection, this is a no brainer.</text>< time>

<user_id>103702791758218889250<//user_id>< name>
Viola D.< /name>
< time>
1527389993615< /time>
<rate>5< /rate><Review>I took my first class at ILKB about three weeks ago because I am completely out of shape. I have tried several forms of exercise (Mama Bootcamp, Crossfit (yuck!!!), walking the neighborhood), but couldn‚Äôt find a thing that I could stick with long-term. Kickboxing is very different - because of the variety of exercises the workout offers, I don‚Äôt feel it will get dull as fast.

Each session is an hour long and can be broken up as follows:
~20 minute warm up (running, squats, push ups, lunges, burpees, etc.)
~5 minutes stretching
~25 minutes bag work (punching, kicking)
~5 minutes partner drills
~5 minutes stretching

At each session there are about three coaches present who will walk around and help participants improve their techniques. I was pleased to see people there of all ages and fitness levels. I would say the average age of the participants is about 35-40 years old. Staff is super welcoming, friendly, and supportive of any newcomers and present members.

The gym itself is very nice as well. The main room has about 22 bags and so far it has not been so crowded that I‚Äôve had to share with anyone. While the classes are co-ed (although predominantly female), there are two locker rooms, one for each gender. You can bring a lock to secure your belongings. Another nice thing is that there is a water station that provides filtered water. Overall, the gym is very clean and you use wipes to clean your workout station after the class.

ILKB offers a great intro deal that includes gloves for you to keep. If you decide to sign up long term, it is about $140/month for a 12-month contract and about $160/month for a 7-month contract. Pricey, but I found this cost pretty on par with other places. If you sign up, you get free hand wraps. You can also pay per visit ($16-20 per class).

ILKB offers weekly ‚ÄúPartner perks‚Äù where you get a discount at a certain establishment each week if you prove your membership. There are also monthly special events, such as DJ nights.

The only thing that I consider as a negative about ILKB is that the music is super loud. I‚Äôm deaf on the right and have to take great care to protect my good ear. If you plan on going often, I would recommend bringing ear plugs to prevent long term hearing damage.

Overall, ILKB is a great place to begin / continue your journey to fitness!</Review>< Pictures>

<Rating>1</Rating><Review>My toilets tank stopped receiving water and I decided to call a couple places to see what it would be to have it looked at. This place was the first one I called.

They said for $89 they could come out and diagnose the problem and give me an estimate on what it would be to fix it. While I was on the phone with them I found a couple other options for $50 to come out and do the same thing, so I told them thanks, I will think about it and give them a call back. The lady on the phone then told me hold on, let me talk to the manager and I can get that $89 service fee waived, and so I just went ahead and decided to use them.

The guy who came out was great, nice professional etc. He took a look at my toilet and was able to tell me the problem was my corroded shut off valve stopping the water flow and he did this by connecting a feeder hose to see if water was still flowing just somehow being blocked by the valve. He was quick to diagnose the problem and clear on what it was.
Then I asked for an estimate for this repair. It was $400 - the $89 dollar service fee credit which goes toward the repair so it brought my grand total to $311. That price was absolutely outrageous. The part was a $12 dollar part from home depot. All you need is a wrench to remove and replace it. For me to shut off my water, and remove/replace this piece took me 10 minutes. There isnt anything special involved or any fancy special tools required to do this. It was as simple as unscrewing something and screwing the new one on (and shutting off the water before doing this) It is not rocket science. I have no experience with plumbing and I did it myself.

Anyway the 1 start review is because of the insane pricing. $400 for coming over and replacing a 10$ piece? The labor doesn't even take 20 minutes.

Anyway, I told the guy I was just going to fix it myself because $400 is a bit much unless you could bring the price down. He was firm on the pricing, and said its set by management at most he could call and ask but he knows they wont change it so I went ahead and ended up paying the $89 service fee and that was that.

What confuses me is he could of just knocked like 100 off the price and it would of still been outrageous but I'd of done it. I don't know anyone who wouldn't be happy to make over $200 just to screw some part on. As long as its not totally obscence pricing I'd go with it, but less then 20 minutes of basic labor and screwing on a part that costs 12$ at home depot that they carry for $400 is their normal pricing? <user_id>116789943246902844422</user_id><user_name>Irene Wolfley< /user_name><date>1530121407230</date>< rating>
1<//rating>
< text>
My toilets tank stopped receiving water and I decided to call a couple places to see what it would be to have it looked at. This place was the first one I called.

They said for $89 they could come out and diagnose the problem and give me an estimate on what it would be to fix it. While I was on the phone with them I found a couple other options for $50 to come out and do the same thing, so I told them thanks, I will think about it and give them a call back. The lady on the phone then told me hold on, let me talk to the manager and I can get that $89 service fee waived, and so I just went ahead and decided to use them.

The guy who came out was great, nice professional etc. He took a look at my toilet and was able to tell me the problem was my corroded shut off valve stopping the water flow and he did this by connecting a feeder hose to see if water was still flowing just somehow being blocked by the valve. He was quick to diagnose the problem and clear on what it was.
Then I asked for an estimate for this repair. It was $400 - the $89 dollar service fee credit which goes toward the repair so it brought my grand total to $311. That price was absolutely outrageous. The part was a $12 dollar part from home depot. All you need is a wrench to remove and replace it. For me to shut off my water, and remove/replace this piece took me 10 minutes. There isnt anything special involved or any fancy special tools required to do this. It was as simple as unscrewing something and screwing the new one on (and shutting off the water before doing this) It is not rocket science. I have no experience with plumbing and I did it myself.

Anyway the 1 start review is because of the insane pricing. $400 for coming over and replacing a 10$ piece? The labor doesn't even take 20 minutes.

Anyway, I told the guy I was just going to fix it myself because $400 is a bit much unless you could bring the price down. He was firm on the pricing, and said its set by management at most he could call and ask but he knows they wont change it so I went ahead and ended up paying the $89 service fee and that was that.

What confuses me is he could of just knocked like 100 off the price and it would of still been outrageous but I'd of done it. I don't know anyone who wouldn't be happy to make over $200 just to screw some part on. As long as its not totally obscence pricing I'd go with it, but less then 20 minutes of basic labor and screwing on a part that costs 12$ at home depot that they carry for $400 is their normal pricing? You'd have to be a complete idiot to go with that.</text>

< review>
John Stevenson Plumbing was the second plumber I called. First, I tried our regular plumber, but they wanted to charge me their "after-hours" rate at 3:30 in the afternoon and couldn't get anyone here for at least 2 hours. Forget that! I had an active leak I couldn't stop.

When I called JSP, they not only said they would be charging their daytime prices, but they don't charge by the hour--they charge by the job, by what actually needs to be done. Refreshing! Then they had a plumber here in less than 30 minutes, and he was the Field Supervisor, no less.

He was friendly, knowledgeable, and quick. He gave me an estimate, including a new-client discount of about 10%, and explained what he was going to do. We had a whole new pressure regulator and shutoff valve in about an hour! He cleaned up the space, gave us some helpful recommendations for avoiding future leaks, a quick tutorial on turning off the water at the street (which I couldn't figure out how to do before), how to bleed air out of the water lines, and was on his way.

Highly recommended!</review>

<Review>I have to say that I have used this company before, but feel very disappointed to recently learn that the information that I received from their service representative was incorrect. At the time of the service inspection, the service man showed me what he believed was rust or deterioration, so he unplugged my furnace and told me that I was in danger of having CO2 come into my house because of what he had found. He had shown me a red marking area inside one of the cylinders with a small flashlight explaining that the cavity had deteriorated.  After explaining to my husband later on the phone about this diagnosis, he found this hard to believe since we have had this company come before for yearly service to maintain our furnace and to prevent such thing from happening. My husband was perplexed since he felt  ‚Äúwhy bother with the yearly service checks if the deterioration  was never mentioned previously or caught earlier?‚Äù So, we phoned another company who came  to perform their own inspection.  What they found was not rust nor deterioration, but conduit tape that was visible on the edge of the interior of the furnace.  They used a probe camera and looked inside and showed me personally what was there...  I could definitely see that this was not rust nor any peeling of the surface of the furnace nor deterioration as I had been led to believe. The new company checked for CO2 readings and found none! <Rating>5<//Rating>< text>
We had a recent experience with John Stevenson Plumbing and HVAC for HVAC repair during the hot summer months. I did not expect to locate a company online with such positive reviews regarding customer service so quickly. The team at John Stevenson dispatched (Juan) to our resident within one to two hours are professionally confirming our appointment. When the service technician showed up (Tom), he politely called to confirm his arrival. This was ideal since we have two little ones at home napping.

John‚Äôs customer service was exceptional. Open communication on the issue, presented resolutions on the spot and utilized their smart device (IPad) to efficiently choose the products needed to fix the issue. After install, they cleaned up right away and followed through with a phone call to check in on the experience.

I had additional questions and contact their operations manager, Destry. Understanding that during this season, customers can get impatient and needy to fix their problem, Destry a very high level of knowledge and customer service to answer my questions.

Overall, the experience was positive. As a home owner with not much knowledge on HVAC systems, I felt I could trust a company with 30+ years of experience. From understanding the immediate need to fix issues and implementation on problem solving, the team knew how to get it done. Top that off with excellent customer service, Destry‚Äôs team is the choice!<//text>

Concerned we called John Stevenson who came out and charged us $89 to provide a quote of $610 to replace the gas valve. They also provided an alternative quote to upgrade to a new furnace.
